<paragraph id="5A772B55FFC52A5E498BA6D3FA6EFD2F" blockId="60.[151,1437,402,1977]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="68BCF747FFC52A5E498BA6D3FEF1FD12" bold="true" box="[199,268,690,716]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Mine.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="C2F337D0FFC52A5E4850A6D3FE7BFD12" box="[284,390,690,716]" captionStart="FIGURES 130–137" captionStartId="47.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[159,1416,196,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-15@47.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 130–137. Figures 130–133: Liriomyza amoena (Meigen); 130: mine in Sambucus nigra leaf; 131–132: posterior segments of puparium; 131: lateral view; 132: posterior view. 133: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 134–137: Liriomyza tropaeoli spec. nov.; 134: mine in Tropaeolum majus leaf; 135: “pupal blisters” with puparia; 136–137: posterior segments of puparium; 136: lateral view; 137: posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158639" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158639/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Figs. 134</figureCitation>
) The larva forms a whitish-green linear upper surface mine that diverges from the base of the leaf along several veins. Pupation takes place inside the mine on the lower leaf surface subepidermally (
<figureCitation id="C2F337D0FFC52A5E4C68A6B7FA7BFD2F" box="[1316,1414,726,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 130–137" captionStartId="47.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[159,1416,196,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-15@47.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 130–137. Figures 130–133: Liriomyza amoena (Meigen); 130: mine in Sambucus nigra leaf; 131–132: posterior segments of puparium; 131: lateral view; 132: posterior view. 133: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 134–137: Liriomyza tropaeoli spec. nov.; 134: mine in Tropaeolum majus leaf; 135: “pupal blisters” with puparia; 136–137: posterior segments of puparium; 136: lateral view; 137: posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158639" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158639/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 135</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5A772B55FFC52A5E498BA69BFAB2FC5E" blockId="60.[151,1437,402,1977]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="68BCF747FFC52A5E498BA69BFEB5FCCA" bold="true" box="[199,328,762,788]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Puparium.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="C2F337D0FFC52A5E4817A69BFDF8FCCA" box="[347,517,762,788]" captionStart="FIGURES 130–137" captionStartId="47.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[159,1416,196,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-15@47.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 130–137. Figures 130–133: Liriomyza amoena (Meigen); 130: mine in Sambucus nigra leaf; 131–132: posterior segments of puparium; 131: lateral view; 132: posterior view. 133: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 134–137: Liriomyza tropaeoli spec. nov.; 134: mine in Tropaeolum majus leaf; 135: “pupal blisters” with puparia; 136–137: posterior segments of puparium; 136: lateral view; 137: posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158639" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158639/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Figs. 136, 137</figureCitation>
) Straw-coloured, translucent, glossy, 
<quantity id="9D3086B0FFC52A5E4AF0A69BFBEBFCCB" box="[956,1046,762,789]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
long, with distinct segmentation; surface quite smooth except for narrow spine bands. Posterior spiracles set on stout conical protuberances that are entirely separate; brown, with numerous minute sessile bulbs in a kidney-shaped arrangement. Anal plate brown, scarcely protruding above the surface of the puparium viewed from the side and directed ventro-posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5A772B55FFC52A5E498BA7EBFDDEFBEB" blockId="60.[151,1437,402,1977]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="68BCF747FFC52A5E498BA7EBFDD9FC7A" bold="true" box="[199,548,906,932]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Cephalopharyngeal skeleton.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="C2F337D0FFC52A5E4B79A7EBFD68FC7B" box="[565,661,906,933]" captionStart="FIGURES 525–530" captionStartId="127.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[202,1412,200,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-15@127.[151,1435,181,1798]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="FIGURES 525–530. Liriomyza tropaeoli spec. nov.; 525: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 526: frontal view of head; 527: head viewed from the side; 528: dorsal view showing head, scutum and scutellum; 529: thorax viewed from the side; 530: oviscape and spermathecae proportionally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158850/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 525</figureCitation>
) Right mouthhook much larger than the left, each with rounded abducted portion directed ventro-anteriorly and bearing two accessory teeth. Intermediate sclerite long, massive, slightly curved dorsally, 1.37× as long as maximum height of left mouthhook. The mouthhook and the intermediate sclerite centrally and ventrally are strongly sclerotized, the intermediate sclerite dorsally and the pharyngeal sclerite much less so. Indentation index 85.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5A772B55FFC52A5E498BA05FFD78FAD2" blockId="60.[151,1437,402,1977]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="68BCF747FFC52A5E498BA05FFE5EFB86" bold="true" box="[199,419,1086,1112]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Adult description.</emphasis>
Head. (
<figureCitation id="C2F337D0FFC52A5E4B4EA05FFD56FB87" box="[514,683,1086,1113]" captionStart="FIGURES 525–530" captionStartId="127.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[202,1412,200,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-15@127.[151,1435,181,1798]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="FIGURES 525–530. Liriomyza tropaeoli spec. nov.; 525: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 526: frontal view of head; 527: head viewed from the side; 528: dorsal view showing head, scutum and scutellum; 529: thorax viewed from the side; 530: oviscape and spermathecae proportionally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158850/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Figs. 526, 527</figureCitation>
) Orbit slightly projecting above eye in profile, especially on the frontal area; 2 orb s, 2 fr s; frorb sta in one row, reclinate, very sparse, short; orbit wide (frontal view); lunule narrowing posteriorly, reaching the level of the anterior fr s; gena medially 0.36× as high as maximum height of eye; gena deepest in posterior part; pped flattened apically viewed from the side. Colour: head yellow with the exception of narrow dark area behind eye (both vt s on the yellow ground) and back head (ocp and m ocp scl); pubescence of pped yellow; all head setae and arista black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5A772B55FFC52A5E498BA176FE99FAA6" blockId="60.[151,1437,402,1977]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="68BCF747FFC52A5E498BA176FEFCFAEE" box="[199,257,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Wing</emphasis>
: (
<figureCitation id="C2F337D0FFC52A5E4855A177FE84FAEF" box="[281,377,1302,1329]" captionStart="FIGURES 531–536" captionStartId="128.[151,264,1835,1859]" captionTargetBox="[189,1385,199,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-18@128.[151,1435,181,1811]" captionTargetPageId="128" captionText="FIGURES 531–536. Liriomyza tropaeoli spec. nov.; 531: wing; 532: epandrium viewed from the side; 533: subepandrial sclerite and postgonites; 534: hypandrium; 535: phallus and epiphallus viewed from the side; 536: ejaculatory apodeme." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158854" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158854/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 531</figureCitation>
) Hyaline with greyish undertone; costal vein greyish-black, ending slightly after M 
<subScript id="C64C2910FFC52A5E4C65A148FACCFAE9" attach="left" box="[1321,1329,1321,1335]" fontSize="6" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">1</subScript>
; last section of CuA 
<subScript id="C64C2910FFC52A5E486CA12CFED5FA85" attach="left" box="[288,296,1357,1371]" fontSize="6" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">1</subScript>
2.3× as long as penultimate; calypter yellow, margin and fringe grey. Wing length: 
<quantity id="9D3086B0FFC52A5E4DAEA15BFAC4FA8B" box="[1250,1337,1338,1365]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
in male, 
<quantity id="9D3086B0FFC52A5E49DBA13FFF10FAA7" box="[151,237,1374,1401]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="mm" value="1.7">1.7 mm</quantity>
in female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5A772B55FFC52A5E498BA1E2FB13FA3A" blockId="60.[151,1437,402,1977]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="68BCF747FFC52A5E498BA1E2FEB7FA42" box="[199,330,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Mesonotum</emphasis>
: (
<figureCitation id="C2F337D0FFC52A5E482EA1E3FDFBFA43" box="[354,518,1410,1437]" captionStart="FIGURES 525–530" captionStartId="127.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[202,1412,200,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-15@127.[151,1435,181,1798]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="FIGURES 525–530. Liriomyza tropaeoli spec. nov.; 525: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 526: frontal view of head; 527: head viewed from the side; 528: dorsal view showing head, scutum and scutellum; 529: thorax viewed from the side; 530: oviscape and spermathecae proportionally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158850/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Figs. 528, 529</figureCitation>
) Brownish-black, shining viewed from above; sctl mainly yellow, black laterally, both ap sctl s and b sctl s on the yellow ground; 1+3 dc s; acr s sparse in 5 irregular rows at level of 2 
<superScript id="ADBD861DFFC52A5E4C46A1C7FAE7FA6A" attach="left" box="[1290,1306,1446,1460]" fontSize="6" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">nd</superScript>
postsutural dc s; halters bright yellow; all legs yellow with brown dusting except yellow ventral femur surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5A772B55FFC52A5E498BA18FFD98F8F6" blockId="60.[151,1437,402,1977]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="68BCF747FFC52A5E498BA18FFE88F9D6" box="[199,373,1518,1544]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Male genitalia:</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="C2F337D0FFC52A5E48C9A18FFDD4F9D7" box="[389,553,1518,1545]" captionStart="FIGURES 531–536" captionStartId="128.[151,264,1835,1859]" captionTargetBox="[189,1385,199,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-18@128.[151,1435,181,1811]" captionTargetPageId="128" captionText="FIGURES 531–536. Liriomyza tropaeoli spec. nov.; 531: wing; 532: epandrium viewed from the side; 533: subepandrial sclerite and postgonites; 534: hypandrium; 535: phallus and epiphallus viewed from the side; 536: ejaculatory apodeme." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158854" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158854/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Figs. 532–536</figureCitation>
) Shape of epandrium–hypandrium complex is typical for the genus, but shape of phallus differs from other species. Ventral apical part of epandrium acute at an angle of 85°, with one posteroventral spine. Postgonite long, with one long, stout and curved tooth. Subepandrial sclerite wider than long, with broad, slightly sclerotized proximal lobes, bearing one strong seta media-laterally and narrow, curved distal lobes bearing one stout spine. Hypandrium U-shaped, with narrow, long arms; pregonite bears one long seta directed media-anteriorly. Distiphallus weakly sclerotized, cylindrical, as long as bulb of sperm duct. Hypophallus hooklike, narrowly strongly sclerotized postero-ventrally and membranous anteriorly. Ejaculatory apodeme triangular, dramatically widened apically, with short stem and slender base. Sperm sac entirely membranous, 0.5× as high as height of apodeme. Phallus 
<quantity id="9D3086B0FFC52A5E4883A36FFDD8F8F7" box="[463,549,1806,1833]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="mm" value="0.3">0.3 mm</quantity>
long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5A772B55FFC52A5E498BA353FA9AF84A" blockId="60.[151,1437,402,1977]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="68BCF747FFC52A5E498BA353FE70F892" box="[199,397,1842,1868]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Female genitalia:</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="C2F337D0FFC52A5E48D0A353FE06F893" box="[412,507,1842,1869]" captionStart="FIGURES 525–530" captionStartId="127.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[202,1412,200,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-15@127.[151,1435,181,1798]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="FIGURES 525–530. Liriomyza tropaeoli spec. nov.; 525: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 526: frontal view of head; 527: head viewed from the side; 528: dorsal view showing head, scutum and scutellum; 529: thorax viewed from the side; 530: oviscape and spermathecae proportionally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158850/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 530</figureCitation>
) Spermathecae are unequal in size, dark brown, obovate. The largest spermatheca is 0.25× as high as height of folded 8 
<superScript id="ADBD861DFFC52A5E4B59A337FDDFF8BA" attach="left" box="[533,546,1878,1892]" fontSize="6" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">th</superScript>
segment. Length of more sclerotized portion of spermathecal duct 1.66× as long as height of spermatheca; weakly sclerotized portion distinctly narrowed unlike that of 
<taxonomicName id="9DC850D6FFC52A5E4D24A31AFB14F84A" baseAuthorityName="Kaltenbach" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[1128,1257,1914,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bryoniae">
<emphasis id="68BCF747FFC52A5E4D24A31AFB14F84A" box="[1128,1257,1914,1940]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">L. bryoniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="C2F337D0FFC52A5E4DB4A31BFAA1F84A" box="[1272,1372,1914,1940]" captionStart="FIGURES 470–474" captionStartId="117.[151,264,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[162,1408,198,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-15@117.[151,1435,181,1744]" captionTargetPageId="117" captionText="FIGURES 470–474. Liriomyza bryoniae (Kaltenbach); 470: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 471: frontal view of head; 472: head viewed from the side; 473: thorax viewed from the side; 474: oviscape and spermathecae proportionally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158794" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158794/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 474</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
